        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002297": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002297",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002298": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002298",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000000138\">[9]</$link><br>\n[ Middle Argos means the Peleponnese which, however, is never so called in the “Iliad”. I presume “middle” means “middle between the two Greek-speaking countries of Asia Minor and Sicily, with South Italy”; for that parts of Sicily and also large parts, though not the whole of South Italy, were inhabited by Greek-speaking races centuries before the Dorian colonisations can hardly be doubted. The Sicians, and also the Sicels, both of them probably spoke Greek.]</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002299": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002299",
