        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002397": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002397",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002398": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002398",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000000308\">[34]</$link><br>\n[ See illustration on opposite page. The yard is typical of many that may be seen in Sicily. The existing ground-plan is probably unmodified from Odyssean, and indeed long pre-Odyssean times, but the earlier buildings would have no arches, and would, one would suppose, be mainly timber. The Odyssean {Greek} were the sheds that ran round the yard as the arches do now. The {Greek} was the one through which the main entrance passed, and which was hence “noisy,” or reverberating. It had an upper story in which visitors were often lodged.]</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002399": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002399",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002400": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002400",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p><a></a></p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002401": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002401",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002402": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002402",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000000308\">[35]</$link><br>\n[ This journey is an impossible one. Telemachus and Pisistratus would have been obliged to drive over the Taygetus range, over which there has never yet been a road for wheeled vehicles. It is plain therefore that the audience for whom the “Odyssey” was written was one that would be unlikely to know anything about the topography of the Peloponnese, so that the writer might take what liberties she chose.]</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002403": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002403",
