            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002775",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002776": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002776",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-769d3732d4c38307-4b6aff twpub-769d3732d4c38307-39c75b twpub-769d3732d4c38307-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p class=\"footnote\"><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000001246\">[125]</$link><br>\n[ See The Authoress of the Odyssey, pp. 140, 141. The real reason for sending Telemachus to Pylos and Lacedaemon was that the authoress might get Helen of Troy into her poem. He was sent at the only point in the story at which he could be sent, so he must have gone then or not at all.]</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002777": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/769d3732d4c38307/text/000002777",
